# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combustion-chamber
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:combustion-chamber/aeolipile] This claim was denied by Spanish authorities.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:combustion-chamber/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:combustion-chamber/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] In the current Alfa Romeo world the "Twin Spark" name usually refers to the dual ignition engines installed in Alfa Romeo cars.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The 8-valve engine was fitted initially to the Alfa Romeo 75 but also the 164 and 155.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The 16-valve engines appeared in the 145, 146, 155, 156, 147, 166, Alfa Romeo GTV & Spider and Alfa Romeo GT models.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The TS series are all twin cam 4-cylinder inline engines.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The original 8-valve engine was derived from Alfa's Twin Cam family, and featured a light alloy (silicon enhanced aluminium alloy) block + head, wet-cooled iron cylinder liners, and the camshafts were driven by a single duplex timing chain.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] So, similar design to the earlier and famous Alfa Romeo Twin Cam engines, but with narrower valve angle and double ignition on this model.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The later 16-valve engines were part of Fiat's "Pratola Serra" (B family) modular engine series, and had a heavier cast-iron block engine, with an alloy head, and the camshafts were belt driven.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The Twin Spark name comes from the fact that there are two spark plugs per cylinder.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] It was cast iron for its higher beam strength, less complexity and hence lower production costs.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] When new, these engines were notable for their high efficiency as demonstrated by the BMEP (brake mean effective pressures) exerted upon the piston crowns.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The two sparks plugs on the 8V Alfa Twin Spark engines fire at the same time and are symmetrically placed around the vertical line passing through the intake and exhaust valve centers.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The flame front travels less distance which allows less ignition advance to be used.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Also, leaner mixtures can also be tolerated for better fuel economy.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The 8V engine also has 8 identical spark plugs.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] There is no room for a centrally positioned spark plug due to 2-valve design which uses rather large 44 mm diameter inlet valve on the 2.0 engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] On the newer models using the 8V engine the system uses the popular wasted spark system as well.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] (as also used in Ford EDIS), combining one coil for 2 plugs on opposite phase sister cylinders like 1-4, 2-3 on 4 cylinder engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] On the Alfa 16V Twin Spark engines one spark plug is ideally located in the centre of the cylinder, as is common in virtually all multi-valve configuration engines.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] In order to accommodate a second spark plug in the 4-valve combustion chamber, a smaller diameter spark plug is located the very edge of the combustion chamber between an inlet and an exhaust valve.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The location of the additional plug means that its impact on maximum performance is marginal.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] However the engine is able to idle smoothly in very lean conditions (up to 18:1 AFR), this suggests the addition plug is here to improve combustion efficiency under light loads.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The next generation Alfa fours, the JTS engines lost the second plugs gained direct injection and increased performance.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The TS 16V engines, 1.6, 1.8 and 2.0, all use a 10 mm diameter and a 14 mm diameter long life platinum electrode spark plug per cylinder.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The spark plugs have a replacement interval of 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The 16 Valve engine features individual 'coil over plug' ignition where the timing of the ignition is controlled directly by the Bosch engine management system, with each coil firing two spark plugs simultaneously.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] So in this configuration each coil services two spark plugs and each cylinder is serviced by two coils.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] In case of a coil failure one of two plugs would still work.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Ignition systems that fire a plug in a cylinder on its exhaust stroke are referred to as a wasted spark ignition system; as the spark ignites nothing and so is 'wasted'.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] In the 16 Valve Twin Spark 4 coils are required by the eight plugs, so production economy was unlikely to be a factor in the adoption of a wasted spark system.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] On the later CF3 (2001 on Euro 3 emissions standard) 16v TS the four coils fire both spark plugs in one cylinder (so not 1 & 4 and 2 & 3 as pairs), and may not be a wasted spark system.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The potential benefits of each coil being associated with one cylinder being: halving the firing frequency - the coil is only required to fire every 720° crankshaft rotation rather than every 360° crankshaft rotation.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] This would double coil saturation time, reducing coil load and improving spark quality at high rpm.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Some Bosch engine management system have the ability to advance and retard ignition timing in individual cylinders, which would be impossible in the CF1 and CF2 configurations as each cylinder is serviced by two coils, but could be used in the CF3 setup.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The engines also incorporate two other devices to enhance the performance under operation, the Camshaft Phase Variator and the Variable Intake Length Control (or Modular Inlet Manifold in Alfaspeak) on the later (plastic cam cover) 1.8- and 2.0-litre versions.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Where both these variable systems are deployed they are controlled in tandem by the Bosch Motronic Engine Management ECU in response to rpm, load, and throttle position.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The advancing of the inlet camshaft opens and closes the intake valves earlier in the inlet cycle.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] This allows the filling of the cylinders with air/fuel mix to begin and end earlier when in advanced position thus starting to compress the mix earlier.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Or the compression phase to begin later (when in not advanced cam state) by delaying the intake valve closure.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The actual compression of the gases can begin only after the closure of the inlet valves so by varying the intake valve closure moment (with the variator) the effective compression ratio can be reduced in not-advanced position.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] This has benefits as a way to reduce the effective compression ratio but still keep the expansion ratio as before so to lower the compression phase mechanical losses.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] When the intake valve is also opened earlier in relation to the closing of the exhaust valves, the valve overlap (the period both inlet and exhaust valves are simultaneously open) is also increased at this mode.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] This promotes the scavenging effect of the exiting exhaust which causes a partial vacuum in the cylinder to further assist in filling the cylinder with a fresh charge.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Also this increased overlap, may cause part of the exhaust gases to re-enter in this way make it function like internal EGR.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] As with similar inlet cam phasing systems like BMW VANOS the phasing is returned to the retarded state at higher rpm to improve power and efficiency as inlet gas dynamics change with rpm.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The short inlet ducts being tuned to the higher frequency and thus shorter inlet duct pressure wave.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] On the 16V engines the camshaft variator is used to enhance the performance/emissions but also might be the source to the common 'diesel noise' problem often seen on high mileage used models which used the earlier internals of the variator.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The same variator system is also used in many Fiat/Lancia engines like one used in Lancia Kappa 5-cylinder engine, some Fiat Bravo/Fiat Marea engines, Fiat Barchetta, Fiat Coupe, Fiat Stilo etc. models.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The Alfa Romeo Modular Inlet Manifold is a variable intake system fitted to the later CF2 1.8 and 2.0 litre Twin Spark engines.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] It operates by switching between two separate air intake runners of different lengths (one pair for each cylinder) to either shorten or lengthen the path from the end of the intake runner (within the plenum) to the inlet valves.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The system is manifold vacuum-assisted servo-operated, and controlled directly by the Bosch engine management system, as described above.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Tuned-length inlet runners operate by using the harmonics created by within the inlet tract/runner by the opening and closing of the inlet valves and flow of gas during the inlet cycle.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Each runner is effectively a velocity stack which reflects a positive pressure wave back down the inlet runner to maximise cylinder filling with fuel/air mix.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The rpm band over which the pressure wave arrives at the open inlet valves and is able to assist in the cylinder filling is set by the length of the runner and is a relatively narrow.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Swapping between runners of differing length broadens the rpm band over which benefits of the tuned inlet runners are achieved, leading to a flatter torque curve and consequently more power across the rev range.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] In addition air-flow within the stock intake tubing between the throttle plate and airbox has also been maximised.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] This includes an 'inlet trumpet' at the end of the intake pipe within the airbox (often referred to as the "cone" by Alfisti) which is designed to improve airflow and fuel metering by reducing turbulence, (and may reflect positive pressure waves back down the intake tube).
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] There is much discussion on about improving performance by removing the trumpet or 'de-coning' as it is often referred to, as the trumpet is thought by some to restrict air flow due to its small inlet cross-section.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Variable valve timing gave the Twin Spark engine very good performance for its cubic capacity, but it is one of the weaker areas of the 16-valve engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The original variator that controls the cam timing is prone to wear or jam, although replacement part carries a different part number and has improved reliability.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] Symptoms are a slight loss of performance and a diesel type rattle from the top of the engine, which appears at startup and gradually lasts for longer.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] It is therefore advisable to get the variator changed regardless of its apparent condition at the 36,000 mile (60,000 km) cambelt replacement.
[src:combustion-chamber/alfa-romeo-twin-spark-engine] The variator problem is not often seen in the earlier 8V Twin Spark version, as these use a different type of cam timing variator system, this is also the case for later 16v versions used in the Alfa Romeo 156 and the 147 where the weak variator was addressed.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:combustion-chamber/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] A **combustion chamber** is part of an internal combustion engine in which the fuel/air mix is burned.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] For steam engines, the term has also been used for an extension of the firebox which is used to allow a more complete combustion process.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] This contrasts an external combustion engine, where the combustion takes place in a separate part of the engine to where the gas pressure is converted into mechanical energy.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] In spark ignition engines, such as petrol (gasoline) engines, the combustion chamber is usually located in the cylinder head.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The engines are often designed such that the bottom of combustion chamber is roughly in line with the top of the engine block.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Modern engines with overhead valves or overhead camshaft(s) use the top of the piston (when it is near top dead centre) as the bottom of the combustion chamber.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Above this, the sides and roof of the combustion chamber include the intake valves, exhaust valves and spark plug.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] This forms a relatively compact combustion chamber without any protrusions to the side (i.e. all of the chamber is located directly above the piston).
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Common shapes for the combustion chamber are typically similar to one or more half-spheres (such as the hemi, pent-roof, wedge or kidney-shaped chambers).
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The older flathead engine design uses a "bathtub"-shaped combustion chamber, with an elongated shape that sits above both the piston and the valves (which are located beside the piston).
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] IOE engines combine elements of overhead valve and flathead engines; the intake valve is located above the combustion chamber, while the exhaust valve is located below it.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The shape of the combustion chamber, intake ports and exhaust ports are key to achieving efficient combustion and maximising power output.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Cylinder heads are often designed to achieve a certain "swirl" pattern (rotational component to the gas flow) and turbulence, which improves the mixing and increases the flow rate of gasses.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The shape of the piston top also affects the amount of swirl.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Another design feature to promote turbulence for good fuel/air mixing is squish, where the fuel/air mix is "squished" at high pressure by the rising piston.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The location of the spark plug is also an important factor, since this is the starting point of the *flame front* (the leading edge of the burning gasses) which then travels downwards towards the piston.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Good design should avoid narrow crevices where stagnant "end gas" can become trapped, reducing the power output of the engine and potentially leading to engine knocking.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Most engines use a single spark plug per cylinder, however some (such as the 1986-2009 Alfa Romeo Twin Spark engine) use two spark plugs per cylinder.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Direct injection engines usually give better fuel economy but indirect injection engines can use a lower grade of fuel.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Harry Ricardo was prominent in developing combustion chambers for diesel engines, the best known being the *Ricardo Comet*.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] In a continuous flow system, for example a jet engine combustor, the pressure is controlled and the combustion creates an increase in volume.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The combustion chamber in gas turbines and jet engines (including ramjets and scramjets) is called the combustor.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The combustor is fed with high pressure air by the compression system, adds fuel and burns the mix and feeds the hot, high pressure exhaust into the turbine components of the engine or out the exhaust nozzle.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] If the gas velocity changes, thrust is produced, such as in the nozzle of a rocket engine.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Considering the definition of combustion chamber used for internal combustion engines, the equivalent part of a steam engine would be the firebox, since this is where the fuel is burned.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] However, in the context of a steam engine, the term "combustion chamber" has also been used for a specific area between the firebox and the boiler.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] This extension of the firebox is designed to allow a more complete combustion of the fuel, improving fuel efficiency and reducing build-up of soot and scale.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] The use of this type of combustion chamber is large steam locomotive engines, allows the use of shorter firetubes.
[src:combustion-chamber/combustion-chamber] Micro combustion chambers are the devices in which combustion happens at a very small volume, due to which surface to volume ratio increases which plays a vital role in stabilizing the flame.
